Hi, to be flexible, I wouldn't use the date field type but rather a number field (for timestamps) or a short text field, that i used here. In the "Add entry template" I changed the input html into this: 
```text
<div class="mb-3 pt-3">
  <div class="fw-bold">Date</div>
  <div class="date-field">
date
</div>
</div>

[...]

<script src="https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/flatpickr"></script>
<script>
window.document.addEventListener("DOMContentLoaded", (event) => {
  // Add the flatpickr stylesheet if it is not already there.
  if(!document.getElementById('flatpickr_css')) {
    var link = document.createElement('link');
    link.id = 'flatpickr_css';
    link.rel = 'stylesheet';
    link.href = 'https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/flatpickr/dist/flatpickr.min.
css
';
    document.head.appendChild(link);
  }
  flatpickr('.date-field input');
});
</script>
```
 so basically adding a div with a class around my date field placeholder. At the end of the existing code in the template, the javascript is added. The input field can be easily set via a datepicker provided by the flatpickr.js library now. I am not sure whether the link element can be in the body at any place, therefore I add the css stylesheet via javascript in the header. The stored values are in the form of YYYY-MM-DD. These dates can actually be sorted. If in the output you want a custom formatted date, you can do something like this e.g. in the Single View template: 
```text
<div class="mt-4">
  <span class="fw-bold">date</span>
  <p class="mt-2 date-field-out">
date
</p>
</div>

[...]

<script src="https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/dayjs@1/dayjs.min.js"></script>
<script>
window.document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', (event) => {
  const nodes = document.querySelectorAll('.date-field-out');
  for (let i = 0; i < nodes.length; i++) {
    const value = nodes[i].innerHTML;
    if (value.trim().length > 0) {
      dayjs(value).format('MMMM D, YYYY');
    }
  }
});
</script>
```
 Again, in the existing html, the p element is extended by the class "date-field-out". The javascript loads the day.js library, reads the YYYY-MM-DD date contents and reformats them to the given format. One thing to watch out when using dates, is the timezone and daylight savings time. For this PoC I didn't check any of these issues, but you should be aware of it and may change the code a bit. The mentioned libraries support this, while the plain Date object within javascript treats everything as UTC. HTH , Stephan PS. the square brackets in the code are lost, so whenever the date appears as a link, it's the placeholder with the square brackets. PPS. to have the output of a list view or single view printed as a PDF, you could do something similar that I have done in https://github.com/srobotta/moodle-database-presets/tree/master/personel-list

I have to correct a glitch when attempting to fix weird outputs (when the field is empty). The corrected codeblock in the Single View Template looks like this: 
```text
    const value = nodes[i].innerHTML;
    if (value.trim().length > 0) {
      nodes[i].innerHTML = dayjs(value).format('MMMM D, YYYY');
    }
```

I assume that you have a field set with one field of type file. In my case I named the file type field "pdf". Having this prerequisites in your "Single view template at the bottom you could add the following: 
```text
<script>
document.addEventListener("DOMContentLoaded", () => {
    const a = document.querySelector("#defaulttemplate-single a.data-field-link");
    if (a) {
      const href = a.getAttribute('href');
      if (href && href.substr(-4).toLowerCase() === '.pdf' ) {
        const embed = document.createElement('embed');
        embed.setAttribute('width', '500');
        embed.setAttribute('height', '375');
        embed.setAttribute('src', href);
        embed.setAttribute('type', 'application/pdf');
        a.replaceWith(embed);
      }
    }
});
</script>
```
 The rest of the template remains unchanged. In the template the file is inserted dynamically with the placeholer pdf . That creates a link and an icon in front of it (to illustrate the filetype). This javascript snippet checks for the link, actually checks that there is a pdf linked (only by looking at the suffix of the file). In that case the anchor element is replaced by: 
```text
<embed src="https://url.to.your.moodle/the.pdf" width="500" height="375"  type="application/pdf">
```
 Unfortunately you cannot limit the file upload to a pdf ( AFAIK ) and (just checked) you can fool Moodle by renaming an image to pdf which then brings you a blank embed window. There is no mimetype check when the placeholder is replaced by the icon and link.

Thanks, William. I took a look at the attached files, but I don't think you've incorporated the functionality I was looking for. Ideally, these direct links would be automatically created. I did some playing around and came up with this javascript band-aid solution: 
```text
function init() {
    var tags = document.getElementsByClassName('tags');
    for (var i=0; i<tags.length; i++) {
        tags[i].innerHTML = tags[i].innerHTML.replace(/\w[\w\s]+?(?=<br>)/g, function(n) {
            return "<a href='view.php?d=16&mode=list&perpage=10&filter=1&f_81%5B%5D="+ escape(n) + "'>" + n + "</a>";
        });
    }
};
window.onload = init;
```

